CAPE TOWN – “Made in China” might have a notorious legacy, but one thing that’s made in China is not to be scoffed at: their culture of saving. Last year, China accounted for about a quarter of the world’s gross national savings, with a personal savings rate of 25%. China has one of the world’s highest national savings rates: 46% of gross domestic product. To put this into perspective, studies show that South Africa’s national savings rate is about 16.5%, while Afghanistan has the lowest savings rate in the world: -11%.   From these observations, we can summarise the following lessons that can be learnt from the Chinese savings culture:   Shaun Ruiters is the executive of business development at PPS Investments. – PERSONAL FINANCE